In .NET 6, the `Startup.cs` class has been replaced with the new simplified approach using the `Program.cs` file. To register the `DbContext` in a .NET 6 project, follow these steps:

1. Open the `Program.cs` file.

2. Modify or add the using statements at the beginning of the file:

```csharp
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql.Infrastructure;
```

3. Find the existing `builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();` line in the `Program.cs` file.

4. Right below it, add the following code to register your `DbContext`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddDbContext<InventoryDbContext>(options =>
    options.UseMySql(builder.Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection"),
        mySqlOptions => mySqlOptions.ServerVersion(new Version(8, 0, 20), ServerType.MySql).EnableRetryOnFailure()));
```

Here's how an example `Program.cs` file looks like after making these changes:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Builder;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Hosting;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql.Infrastructure;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Add services to the container.
builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();

builder.Services.AddDbContext<InventoryDbContext>(options =>
        options.UseMySql(builder.Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection"),
        mySqlOptions => mySqlOptions.ServerVersion(new Version(8, 0, 20), ServerType.MySql).EnableRetryOnFailure()));

var app = builder.Build();

// Configure the HTTP request pipeline.
if (!app.Environment.IsDevelopment())
{
    app.UseExceptionHandler("/Home/Error");
    // The default HSTS value is 30 days. You may want to change this for production scenarios, see https://aka.ms/aspnetcore-hsts.
    app.UseHsts();
}

app.UseHttpsRedirection();
app.UseStaticFiles();

app.UseRouting();

app.UseAuthorization();

app.MapControllerRoute(
    name: "default",
    pattern: "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");

app.Run();
```

That's it! You have registered the `DbContext` in your .NET 6 ASP.NET Core application.

Apologies for the confusion in the previous example. It appears the `ServerVersion` property is not available in the newer versions of the `Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql` package. Instead, you can specify the server version directly in the `UseMySql` method. Here's an updated example for registering the `DbContext` in .NET 6:

1. Modify or add the using statements at the beginning of the `Program.cs` file:

```csharp
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
```

2. Find the existing `builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();` line in the `Program.cs` file.

3. Right below it, add the following code to register your `DbContext`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddDbContext<InventoryDbContext>(options =>
        options.UseMySql(
            builder.Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection"),
            new MySqlServerVersion(new Version(8, 0, 20))
        )
);
```

Here's an example `Program.cs` file after these changes:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Builder;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Hosting;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Add services to the container.
builder.Services.AddControllersWithViews();

builder.Services.AddDbContext<InventoryDbContext>(options =>
        options.UseMySql(
            builder.Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection"),
            new MySqlServerVersion(new Version(8, 0, 20))
        )
);

var app = builder.Build();

// Configure the HTTP request pipeline.
if (!app.Environment.IsDevelopment())
{
    app.UseExceptionHandler("/Home/Error");
    // The default HSTS value is 30 days. You may want to change this for production scenarios, see https://aka.ms/aspnetcore-hsts.
    app.UseHsts();
}

app.UseHttpsRedirection();
app.UseStaticFiles();

app.UseRouting();

app.UseAuthorization();

app.MapControllerRoute(
    name: "default",
    pattern: "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");

app.Run();
```

Now you should not receive the `CS1061` error when registering the `DbContext`.

To create an ASP.NET Core application with Blazor pages and Entity Framework (EF) Core for managing a simple inventory system, follow these steps:

1. Install prerequisites

Ensure you have installed the following tools:

- .NET 5 SDK: https://dotnet.microsoft.com/download/dotnet/5.0
- Visual Studio 2019 (version 16.8 or higher): https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/downloads/

2. Create a new Blazor Server App project

Open Visual Studio and create a new Blazor Server App project. In the "Configure your new project" window, provide the following details:

- Project name: `InventoryManagement`
- Location: Choose a directory where you want to save the project
- Solution name: `InventoryManagement`

Click "Create" to create the project.

3. Install package dependencies

Open the `Package Manager Console` (Tools > NuGet Package Manager > Package Manager Console) and run the following commands:

```
Install-Package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore
Install-Package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Tools
Install-Package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design
Install-Package Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql
```

These commands install the necessary Entity Framework Core packages, as well as the MySQL provider (Pomelo) for EF Core.

4. Create an Entity Model for Product

In your "Models" folder, create a new class file `Product.cs` and define the `Product` entity:

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations;

namespace InventoryManagement.Models
{
    public class Product
    {
        [Key]
        public int Id { get; set; }

        [Required]
        [MaxLength(100)]
        public string Name { get; set; }

        [Required]
        [MaxLength(200)]
        public string Description { get; set; }

        [Required]
        public decimal Price { get; set; }

        [Required]
        public int Quantity { get; set; }
    }
}
```

5. Create a DbContext class for the application

In your "Data" folder, create a new file `InventoryDbContext.cs` and implement the DbContext:

```csharp
using InventoryManagement.Models;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;

namespace InventoryManagement.Data
{
    public class InventoryDbContext : DbContext
    {
        public InventoryDbContext(DbContextOptions<InventoryDbContext> options)
            : base(options)
        { }

        public DbSet<Product> Products { get; set; }
    }
}
```

6. Configure the connection string and register DbContext in Startup.cs

Open `appsettings.json` and add the connection string for your MySQL database:

```json
{
  "ConnectionStrings":
  {
    "DefaultConnection": "server=localhost;port=3306;database=InventoryManagement;user=root;password=YOUR_PASSWORD"
  },
  ...
}
```

In `Startup.cs`, configure your DbContext in the `ConfigureServices` method:

```csharp
using InventoryManagement.Data;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql.Infrastructure;
//...
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    //...
    services.AddDbContextPool<InventoryDbContext>(options => options
        .UseMySql(Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection"),
        new MySqlServerVersion(new Version(8, 0, 21)),
        mySqlOptions => mySqlOptions
            .CharSetBehavior(CharSetBehavior.NeverAppend)));

    services.AddRazorPages();
    services.AddServerSideBlazor();
}
```

7. Scaffold the Blazor CRUD pages

Right-click on the "Pages" folder, choose "Add" > "New Scaffolded Item", then select "Razor Pages using Entity Framework (CRUD)".

In the "Add Razor Pages using Entity Framework (CRUD)" window, set the following options:

- Model class: Product (InventoryManagement.Models)
- Data context class: InventoryDbContext (InventoryManagement.Data)
- Razor Pages options: Use the default options

Click "Add" to generate the necessary Blazor pages for the CRUD operations.

8. Run migrations and update the database

In the Package Manager Console, run the following commands:

```
Add-Migration InitialCreate
Update-Database
```

This will create a migration script and update your MySQL database.

9. Generate the product list, and navigation menu

Open `Pages/Products/Index.razor`, and replace the code with:

```csharp
@page "/products"
@using InventoryManagement.Models
@using InventoryManagement.Data
@inject InventoryDbContext _db

<h1>Product List</h1>

<p>
    <a href="Products/Create">Add Product</a>
</p>

<table class="table">
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th>Name</th>
            <th>Description</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Quantity</th>
            <th></th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        @foreach (var product in products)
        {
            <tr>
                <td>@product.Name</td>
                <td>@product.Description</td>
                <td>@product.Price</td>
                <td>@product.Quantity</td>
                <td>
                    <a href="Products/Edit/@product.Id">Edit</a> |
                    <a href="Products/Details/@product.Id">Details</a> |
                    <a href="Products/Delete/@product.Id">Delete</a>
                </td>
            </tr>
        }
    </tbody>
</table> 

@code {
    private List<Product> products;

    protected override async Task OnInitializedAsync()
    {
        products = await _db.Products.ToListAsync();
    }
}
```

Open `Shared/NavMenu.razor` and add a new menu item for the "Products" page:

```csharp
<li class="nav-item px-3">
    <NavLink class="nav-link" href="products">
        <span class="oi oi-list-rich" aria-hidden="true"></span> Products
    </NavLink>
</li>
```

10. Test the application

Press F5 or Ctrl+F5 to run the application. Navigate to "/products" and test the CRUD operations for the inventory system.

To create a RESTful API for a Todo List application, follow the steps below:

1. Install necessary tools and packages

Install Visual Studio or Visual Studio Code, .NET Core SDK, MySQL and EF Core, if you don't have them already.

2. Create a new Web API project

Open a terminal or command prompt and run the following command to create an ASP.NET Core Web App using the Web API template:

```
dotnet new webapi -o TodoApi
cd TodoApi
```

3. Install necessary NuGet Packages

Add the required NuGet packages for EF Core, MySQL, and ASP.NET Core.

```
dotnet add package Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql
dotnet add package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.Design
```

4. Configure the connection string and EF Core

Create an `appsettings.json` file with the following content:

```json
{
  "ConnectionStrings": {
    "DefaultConnection": "server=localhost;port=3306;database=TodoDb;uid=my-username;pwd=my-password;"
  },
  "Logging": {
    "LogLevel": {
      "Default": "Information",
      "Microsoft": "Warning",
      "Microsoft.Hosting.Lifetime": "Information"
    }
  },
  "AllowedHosts": "*"
}
```

Replace `my-username` and `my-password` with your MySQL credentials.

In the `Startup.cs` file, replace the `ConfigureServices` method with the following code:

```c#
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    services.AddDbContext<TodoDbContext>(options =>
        options.UseMySql(Configuration.GetConnectionString("DefaultConnection"),
            new MySqlServerVersion(new Version(8, 0, 25))));
    services.AddControllers();
}
```

5. Create the Todo model

Create a `Todo.cs` file in the Models folder with the following content:

```c#
public class Todo
{
    public long Id { get; set; }
    public string Title { get; set; }
    public string Description { get; set; }
}
```

6. Create the database context

Create a `TodoDbContext.cs` file in the `Data` folder with the following content:

```c#
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using TodoApi.Models;

public class TodoDbContext : DbContext
{
    public TodoDbContext(DbContextOptions<TodoDbContext> options)
        : base(options)
    {
    }

    public DbSet<Todo> Todos { get; set; }
}
```

7. Create and apply the migration

In the terminal, execute the following commands:

```
dotnet ef migrations add InitialCreateTodo
dotnet ef database update
```

8. Create the Todo API controller

Create a `TodoController.cs` file in the Controllers folder with the following content:

```c#
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using TodoApi.Data;
using TodoApi.Models;

[Route("api/[controller]")]
[ApiController]
public class TodoController : ControllerBase

```c#
{
    private readonly TodoDbContext _context;

    public TodoController(TodoDbContext context)
    {
        _context = context;
    }

    // GET: api/Todo
    [HttpGet]
    public async Task<ActionResult<IEnumerable<Todo>>> GetTodos()
    {
        return await _context.Todos.ToListAsync();
    }

    // GET: api/Todo/5
    [HttpGet("{id}")]
    public async Task<ActionResult<Todo>> GetTodo(long id)
    {
        var todo = await _context.Todos.FindAsync(id);

        if (todo == null)
        {
            return NotFound();
        }

        return todo;
    }

    // PUT: api/Todo/5
    [HttpPut("{id}")]
    public async Task<IActionResult> PutTodo(long id, Todo todo)
    {
        if (id != todo.Id)
        {
            return BadRequest();
        }

        _context.Entry(todo).State = EntityState.Modified;

        try
        {
            await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
        }
        catch (DbUpdateConcurrencyException)
        {
            if (!TodoExists(id))
            {
                return NotFound();
            }
            else
            {
                throw;
            }
        }

        return NoContent();
    }

    // POST: api/Todo
    [HttpPost]
    public async Task<ActionResult<Todo>> PostTodo(Todo todo)
    {
        _context.Todos.Add(todo);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();

        return CreatedAtAction("GetTodo", new { id = todo.Id }, todo);
    }

    // DELETE: api/Todo/5
    [HttpDelete("{id}")]
    public async Task<IActionResult> DeleteTodo(long id)
    {
        var todo = await _context.Todos.FindAsync(id);
        if (todo == null)
        {
            return NotFound();
        }

        _context.Todos.Remove(todo);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();

        return NoContent();
    }

    private bool TodoExists(long id)
    {
        return _context.Todos.Any(e => e.Id == id);
    }
}
```

Now the API is ready to use. You can run the application by executing the following command in the terminal:

```
dotnet run
```

This will start the application and the API will be available at `http://localhost:5000/api/todo`.  You can use a tool like Postman or the browser to test the endpoints.

To summarize, we created a RESTful API using ASP.NET Core, EF Core, and MySQL to manage a simple todo list application. The API allows users to create, read, update, and delete todo items, with each item having a title and a description.

`TodoApi.Data` is a namespace used in the example provided above. It's essentially a way to organize related code and classes. In this case, the "Data" namespace is intended to contain data access-related classes such as the DbContext and any other data access logic.

In the example provided above, we create a `TodoDbContext` class in the `TodoApi.Data` namespace:

```csharp
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using TodoApi.Models;

namespace TodoApi.Data
{
    public class TodoDbContext : DbContext
    {
        public TodoDbContext(DbContextOptions<TodoDbContext> options)
            : base(options)
        {
        }

        public DbSet<Todo> Todos { get; set; }
    }
}
```

This `TodoDbContext` class is a data access class derived from EF Core's `DbContext`. It's used for configuring the connection, specifying the entity types (in this case, `Todo` model), and providing access to data through DbSet properties like `Todos`.

To ensure that the `Id` field in the `Todo` class is auto-incremented in the database, we need to define the Id as `Identity` in the model configuration. Modify the `TodoDbContext` class to configure the `Id` property as `Identity` using the Fluent API.

Here is the updated `TodoDbContext` class:

```csharp
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using TodoApi.Models;

namespace TodoApi.Data
{
    public class TodoDbContext : DbContext
    {
        public TodoDbContext(DbContextOptions<TodoDbContext> options)
            : base(options)
        {
        }

        public DbSet<Todo> Todos { get; set; }

        protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
        {
            modelBuilder.Entity<Todo>(entity =>
            {
                entity.Property(e => e.Id)
                    .ValueGeneratedOnAdd()
                    .UseIdentityColumn();
            });
        }
    }
}
```

In the `OnModelCreating` method, we defined a configuration for the `Todo` entity where the `Id` property uses `ValueGeneratedOnAdd` and the `UseIdentityColumn` method. This will ensure that the `Id` field is set as an auto-incrementing primary key in the database.

Now, when you create and apply the migration, the `Id` column will be configured as an auto-increment field within the MySQL database.

To create unit tests for the TodoController using NUnit, follow the steps below:

1. Create a new NUnit test project

Navigate to your solution directory and run the following commands to create a new NUnit test project and add it to your solution:

```
dotnet new nunit -o TodoApi.Tests
dotnet sln add TodoApi.Tests/TodoApi.Tests.csproj
```

2. Add necessary NuGet packages
Navigate to the TodoApi.Tests directory in your terminal and add the required NuGet packages:

```
cd TodoApi.Tests
dotnet add package Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore.InMemory
dotnet add package Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Core
dotnet add package Moq
```

3. Create a test class
Create a file `TodoControllerTests.cs` in the `TodoApi.Tests` project with the following content:

```csharp
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
using Moq;
using TodoApi.Controllers;
using TodoApi.Data;
using TodoApi.Models;
using NUnit.Framework;

namespace TodoApi.Tests
{
    public class TodoControllerTests
    {
        private TodoDbContext _context;
        private TodoController _controller;

        [SetUp]
        public void Setup()
        {
            var options = new DbContextOptionsBuilder<TodoDbContext>()
                .UseInMemoryDatabase(databaseName: "TestDb")
                .Options;

            _context = new TodoDbContext(options);
            _controller = new TodoController(_context);
        }

        [TearDown]
        public void TearDown()
        {
            _context.Database.EnsureDeleted();
        }

        [Test]
        public async Task GetTodos_ReturnsAllTodos()
        {
            // Arrange
            var todos = new List<Todo>
            {
                new Todo { Title = "Task 1", Description = "Description 1" },
                new Todo { Title = "Task 2", Description = "Description 2" }
            };
            _context.AddRange(todos);
            _context.SaveChanges();

            // Act
            var result = await _controller.GetTodos();

            // Assert
            Assert.AreEqual(2, result.Value.Count());
            CollectionAssert.AreEqual(todos, result.Value);
        }

        // Other test methods can be added below
    }
}
```

This code sets up the `TodoDbContext` using the in-memory database, providing an isolated environment for each test method. The database is deleted after each test is executed, ensuring a clean state for the next test.

Within the `TodoControllerTests` class, you can now add other test methods for different tests, such as testing individual endpoints like creating, updating, or deleting todos.

4. Run the tests

You can run the tests from the command line using `dotnet test`:

```
dotnet test
```

Now you have a basic NUnit testing setup for `TodoController`. You can extend it by adding more test methods to cover all the endpoints and scenarios.

Here are the test methods for adding, deleting, and updating todo items in the `TodoControllerTests` class.

```csharp
[Test]
