Now the StatusCode properties should be correctly accessed from the IActionResult, and the tests should run without errors. Run the tests again with `dotnet test`.

When you cast IActionResult to ObjectResult and get a null value, it is usually because the IActionResult returned by the controller's action method is not an instance of ObjectResult or a derived class. The IActionResult return value of a controller action method could be several types: OkObjectResult, BadRequestObjectResult, NotFoundObjectResult, etc. These classes are derived from ObjectResult, but IActionResult might also be a different type, like StatusCodeResult or ViewResult.

For example, consider the following controller action method:

```csharp
[HttpGet("{id}")]
public async Task<ActionResult<Todo>> GetTodo(long id)
{
    var todo = await _context.Todos.FindAsync(id);

    if (todo == null)
    {
        return NotFound(); // Returns a NotFoundResult instance, which is not derived from ObjectResult
    }

    return todo; // Returns an ActionResult<T> instance, which is not derived directly from ObjectResult
}
```

In this case, calling `GetTodo` with a non-existent ID would return a NotFoundResult instance, which is not derived from ObjectResult. Similarly, when the item is found, it implicitly returns a OkObjectResult via `return todo;` instead of ObjectResult.

To handle this case when writing tests, you can check for specific result types, such as NotFoundResult, OkObjectResult, or BadRequestObjectResult. Example test code:

```csharp
[TestCase(1, false)] // Non-existent ID
[TestCase(1, true)] // Existing ID
public async Task GetTodo_ReturnsTodo_OrNotFound(int id, bool exists)
{
    if (exists)
    {
        _context.Todos.Add(new Todo { Title = "Existing Task", Description = "Existing Description" });
        _context.SaveChanges();
    }

    var result = await _controller.GetTodo(id);

    if (exists)
    {
        // Check if the result is OkObjectResult
        var objectResult = result.Result as OkObjectResult;
        Assert.IsNotNull(objectResult);
        Assert.AreEqual(StatusCodes.Status200OK, objectResult.StatusCode);

        // Perform other assertions on the objectResult.Value as needed
    }
    else
    {
        // Check if the result is NotFoundResult
        var notFoundResult = result.Result as NotFoundResult;
        Assert.IsNotNull(notFoundResult);
    }
}
```

In this example, I am using TestCase with parameters to handle both cases: one where the task does not exist, and one where the task exists. If the task exists, I am casting IActionResult to OkObjectResult to work specifically with HTTP 200 status codes. If the task does not exist, I am casting IActionResult to NotFoundResult.

I apologize for any confusion that my previous response may have caused. I see now that there was a mistake regarding the casting to `ObjectResult`. Instead of casting to `ObjectResult`, we can check the type of the instance directly and perform assertions accordingly.

Here's an updated version of the PutTodo test method that ensures validity. This test checks whether the returned `IActionResult` is either a `NoContentResult` or an `ObjectResult` with `Status204NoContent`:

```csharp
[Test]
public async Task PutTodo_UpdatesExistingTodo()
{
    // Arrange
    var todo = new Todo { Title = "Task 1", Description = "Description 1" };
    _context.Add(todo);
    _context.SaveChanges();

    var updatedTodo = new Todo { Id = todo.Id, Title = "Updated Task", Description = "Updated Description" };

    // Act
    var result = await _controller.PutTodo(updatedTodo.Id, updatedTodo);

    // Assert
